# JavaScript and ES6+ Best Practices

## Code Organization
- Use modular architecture
- Implement proper file structure
- Group related functionality
- Keep files focused and small
- Use clear module boundaries
- Avoid circular dependencies

## Naming Conventions
- Use camelCase for variables and functions
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- Use PascalCase for classes and components
- Use descriptive, meaningful names
- Prefix boolean variables with is/has/should/can
- Use verb-based names for functions

## Variables and Constants
- Use const by default
- Use let when variable reassignment needed
- Never use var
- Declare variables in proper scope
- Use destructuring where appropriate
- Keep variable scope minimal

## Functions
- Use arrow functions for callbacks
- Write pure functions when possible
- Keep functions small and focused
- Use proper error handling
- Implement meaningful return types
- Document complex functions

## Async Programming
- Use async/await for asynchronous code
- Avoid callback chains (callback hell)
- Handle promise rejections properly
- Use Promise.all for parallel operations
- Implement proper error handling
- Set timeouts for long-running operations

## Error Handling
- Implement try-catch blocks appropriately
- Throw meaningful error messages
- Log errors with context
- Create custom error classes
- Handle async errors properly
- Never silently catch errors

## Performance Optimization
- Debounce and throttle event handlers
- Implement memoization for expensive operations
- Use lazy loading for modules
- Optimize bundle size
- Avoid memory leaks
- Profile performance regularly

## DOM Manipulation
- Clean up event listeners
- Use event delegation appropriately
- Batch DOM updates
- Avoid unnecessary reflows
- Use DocumentFragment for multiple elements
- Implement proper cleanup functions

## Module System
- Use ES6 named exports (tree-shakeable)
- Avoid default exports when possible
- Implement proper import statements
- Use dynamic imports for code splitting
- Keep module boundaries clear
- Document public APIs

## String Handling
- Use template literals for string interpolation
- Avoid string concatenation
- Use proper string methods
- Implement proper encoding/decoding
- Handle Unicode properly
- Sanitize user input

## Array Operations
- Use array methods (map, filter, reduce)
- Avoid mutating original arrays
- Use proper iteration patterns
- Implement efficient searches
- Use Array.isArray for type checking
- Document array transformations

## Object Handling
- Use object destructuring
- Avoid modifying object prototypes
- Use Object methods appropriately
- Implement proper deep copies
- Use Object.freeze for immutability
- Document object structures

## Type Checking
- Use typeof for type checks
- Implement proper null/undefined checks
- Use strict equality (===, !==)
- Avoid loose equality (==, !=)
- Use Number.isFinite for number checks
- Document expected types

## Regular Expressions
- Use proper regex patterns
- Add comments for complex patterns
- Test regex thoroughly
- Avoid catastrophic backtracking
- Use proper flags
- Document regex purposes

## JSON Operations
- Validate JSON before parsing
- Handle JSON parsing errors
- Implement proper serialization
- Use proper indentation for readability
- Avoid circular references
- Document JSON structures

## Code Quality
- Use proper linting (ESLint)
- Follow consistent formatting
- Remove commented-out code
- Implement proper comments
- Use meaningful variable names
- Keep functions under 50 lines

## Testing
- Write unit tests for functions
- Implement integration tests
- Test error scenarios
- Mock external dependencies
- Use proper test frameworks
- Maintain test coverage > 70%

## Security
- Validate all user input
- Escape output properly
- Use secure random generation
- Handle sensitive data carefully
- Never log sensitive information
- Keep dependencies updated

## Logging and Debugging
- Implement structured logging
- Use appropriate log levels
- Remove console.log from production
- Use debugger appropriately
- Log meaningful information
- Monitor application performance

